OSINT Masterclass: Deconstructing Digital Scams – The myIQ Investigative Case Study

1. Introduction: The Architecture of Digital Deception

In the contemporary digital economy, the proliferation of "dark pattern" subscription models represents a shift from traditional marketing to the engineering of automated billing traps. These systems are meticulously designed to move users through a low-friction "hook" into high-velocity recurring financial obligations. For the Lead OSINT Investigator, Open Source Intelligence has evolved beyond simple research; it is now a tactical mechanism for breaching the corporate veil and enforcing accountability.

The "myIQ Investigation" serves as our primary case study in mapping a global deceptive architecture. The platform presents a front of academic rigor, even issuing formal IQ Certificates—such as the one granted to "Shane Lockhart" with a score of 128—validated by fictitious "Validation Officers" like O. Taylor and D. Miller. However, beneath this layer of "Director of Assessments" signatures lies a multi-jurisdictional web designed to insulate the Ultimate Beneficial Owners (UBO) from liability. This masterclass deconstructs how we breached the initial layer of anonymity to reveal the global machinery of this operation.

2. The Investigative Engine: Disciplined OSINT Workflows

Standard investigative methods frequently fail when confronted with sophisticated digital deceptive operations. These entities utilize Search Engine Optimization (SEO) "cloaking" to bury investigative leads under high-authority noise. To uncover hard evidence, a disciplined workflow is required to bypass this noise and identify unique digital and physical anchors that the operators cannot easily scrub.

Precision Dorking: Bypassing SEO Noise

The breakthrough in the myIQ investigation relied on "Google Dorks"—advanced search queries that target specific, non-obvious data points. We utilized temporal and physical anchors to bypass the brand’s marketing front.

