4. The "Dark Pattern" Financial Model: From Trial to Trap

In professional OSINT, the payment gateway is the "smoking gun." The myIQ platform relies on Maltese Electronic Money Institutions (EMIs) to process global credit card volume that would be flagged by traditional U.S. banking filters for "dark pattern" billing.

The definitive forensic link was identified via bank statements showing the string: "MYIQ.COM/EU ST. JULIAN S MelMT." The "MelMT" identifier is the technical signature for Mellifera Kartiera Limited (Registry IDs: C 77292 and C 107685), operating under the broader brand name Colibrix Ltd.

Gatekeepers of the Money

The Maltese node is supported by specific gatekeepers who provide regulatory legitimacy to this high-risk processing:

* Stephen Balzan: The primary tax consultant and "architect" at the Villa Malitah hub.
* Stanislav Sadykhov & Artjoms Grivkovs: Operational principals managing the Colibrix/Mellifera infrastructure.
* Joseph Camilleri: Chairman of Mellifera, providing essential local regulatory standing.

While the financial treasury is offshore, the ultimate leadership nexus is traced to Jawad Khan, founder of Evernex Pakistan in Islamabad. Khan utilizes "SEO Cloaking" to hide behind search results for a high-profile PIF executive and a Dubai transport owner, masking his role as the architect of the global subscription engine.

5. The Confrontation Strategy: Turning Intelligence into Leverage

Documentation of a scam's architecture fundamentally shifts the power dynamic. In our case study, the support agent ("David") initially attempted a "Partial Refund Gambit," offering to return only the $1.00 trial fee while retaining the $30.00 unauthorized charge.

The investigator countered by presenting the Intelligence Map. By explicitly naming Envest Research (DE), MTA Global (WY), and the Mellifera/Colibrix gateway in Malta, the investigator signaled that the corporate veil was breached. The threat was clear: the victim had the data required to report the specific merchant account to the Maltese regulators, potentially jeopardizing the operators' multi-million dollar payment infrastructure.

The result was a shift from "policy-driven denial" to an immediate concession: "the full refund has already been processed." Operators prioritize the survival of their processing gateways over the retention of a single $30.00 charge.

6. The "Truth-Seeker" Toolkit: Professional OSINT Checklist

Use this "Signal & Trace" methodology to map the architecture of any deceptive digital platform:

* [ ] Dork the Anchors: Use exact-match queries for physical addresses found in Terms of Service and specific billing signatures (e.g., "MelMT").
* [ ] Registry Verification: Cross-reference entities via the Malta Business Registry (MBR) and the WyoBiz portal to identify the registered agents and directors.
* [ ] Technical Footprint Analysis: Analyze the Start of Authority (SOA) and DNS history for developer handles such as "jkhan_evernex" or tracking tags (Google UA codes) that bypass SEO cloaking.
* [ ] Identify the UBO: Look for "Application for Authority" filings in Delaware or shareholder lists in the MBR to identify the Ultimate Beneficial Owner.
* [ ] Show Your Work: When confronting a support agent, present a documented map of their multi-jurisdictional structure. Use their specific gateway ID to force an immediate refund.

In the digital age, clarity and verified data are the ultimate forms of leverage. By replacing confusion with forensic evidence, we move from victimhood to investigative authority.
